So, if the context or Kairos is a set of conditions favorable for performing any task.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:28.000
All this is presented to you on the next slide.

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:34.000
Then context planning is a planning technique, which consists of

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:39.000
1. Identification of typical personal Kairos.

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:42.000
What Kairos do you have?

01:05:42.000 --> 01:05:50.000
2. Establishing the appropriate lists of tasks associated with these Kairos.

01:05:50.000 --> 01:05:59.000
3. Viewing these lists when approaching certain Kairos.

01:05:59.000 --> 01:06:05.000
Let's see how context planning is carried out.

01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:08.000
Attention to the next slide.

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:14.000
It presents context planning in a diary.

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:20.000
So, the first technique is separate sections on typical contexts.

01:06:20.000 --> 01:06:23.000
You take your diary.

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:28.000
You select separate sections of this diary.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:35.000
Client A, Client B, Client C, Project A, Project B, Project C.

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:44.000
And you write all the questions that relate to this client or this project.

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:46.000
Next.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:50.000
The second technique is stickers for flexible tasks.

01:06:50.000 --> 01:06:52.000
What is it?

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:56.000
You agreed to call someone at the end of the month.

01:06:56.000 --> 01:06:59.000
In general, I must say that this is an extremely unsuccessful formulation.

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:03.000
Because the end of the month is a very conditional concept.

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:06.000
For one, the end of the month is 30th and 31st.

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:10.000
Another means that the 25th is already the end of the month.

01:07:10.000 --> 01:07:13.000
Then it is always not very successful.

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:15.000
When we call, there is always a problem.

01:07:15.000 --> 01:07:17.000
And I thought you would call.

01:07:17.000 --> 01:07:18.000
And so on.

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:22.000
So, what can we do in this case?

01:07:22.000 --> 01:07:27.000
We can write down on the 25th to call Ivan Ivanovich.

01:07:27.000 --> 01:07:29.000
We can write it down.

01:07:29.000 --> 01:07:32.000
The 25th has come. We call Ivan Ivanovich.

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:34.000
We find out that he is on a business trip.

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:38.000
We find out that he will come in three days.

01:07:38.000 --> 01:07:40.000
What should we do?

01:07:40.000 --> 01:07:42.000
First.

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:47.000
We try to remember that we need to call Ivan Ivanovich in three days.

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:49.000
Extremely unsuccessful.

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:52.000
It is exactly after the 30th that we will definitely forget about it.

01:07:52.000 --> 01:07:54.000
The second option.

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:58.000
We rewrite this record to the 28th.

01:07:58.000 --> 01:08:00.000
Better.

01:08:00.000 --> 01:08:03.000
Although we spent a certain amount of time on this.

01:08:03.000 --> 01:08:06.000
On the 28th, we call Ivan Ivanovich.

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:08.000
And we are told that he will not be there today.

01:08:08.000 --> 01:08:12.000
He drove in there in the morning for five minutes and left today with the ends.

01:08:12.000 --> 01:08:13.000
What should we do?

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:15.000
Rewrite to tomorrow?

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:18.000
And how long should we rewrite from one page to another?

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:20.000
Stickers in this regard.

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:23.000
A much more convenient tool.

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:29.000
We paste them on the corresponding page of the diary.

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:33.000
If this task has passed to another day.

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:37.000
It takes us a split second to paste this sticker.

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:47.000
In addition, the sticker has the ability to signal to us that we need to solve a particular task.

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:49.000
And finally, the third technique.

01:08:49.000 --> 01:08:53.000
It is called a tab with contextual tasks.

01:08:53.000 --> 01:09:06.000
In the former Soviet Union, maybe some of you have met such a tool called a perfocard.

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:12.000
It was very popular in computing centers, programmers, and developers.

01:09:12.000 --> 01:09:17.000
This is a dense cardboard of a small format.

01:09:17.000 --> 01:09:26.000
On it, as a rule, in addition to its main application, it was very convenient to write down, mark and store something.

01:09:26.000 --> 01:09:36.000
So, this is a sheet of dense cardboard, thin, on which you write down a list of your tasks.

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:41.000
And this sheet is posted on one page of your diary to another.

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:55.000
For example, during lunch, you can meet with Ivanov and Petrov and talk to them about this and that.

01:09:55.000 --> 01:10:06.000
You can write such a task on a perfocard and take it with you when you go to lunch.

01:10:06.000 --> 01:10:15.000
So, naturally, you don't have to carry a diary with you, don't have to look at what tasks you have tied to lunchtime, and so on.

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:20.000
This is what concerns the tab with contextual tasks.

01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:26.000
But these are personal contextual planning techniques.

01:10:26.000 --> 01:10:33.000
Yes, you can, of course, use the context planning technique on Outlook.

