but you will never be in a tight spot.

01:55:10.000 --> 01:55:13.000
Why do we recommend flexible tasks

01:55:13.000 --> 01:55:17.000
to be placed separately, not to include them in the grid?

01:55:17.000 --> 01:55:19.000
This is the main question,

01:55:19.000 --> 01:55:22.000
because in fact, it is more convenient for many of us

01:55:22.000 --> 01:55:25.000
to plan all types of tasks in the grid.

01:55:25.000 --> 01:55:28.000
But look what is happening.

01:55:28.000 --> 01:55:31.000
We are having a tough time,

01:55:31.000 --> 01:55:34.000
because we depend on other people.

01:55:34.000 --> 01:55:38.000
Someone got stuck in traffic and was late for 20 minutes.

01:55:38.000 --> 01:55:41.000
We allocated an hour for the conversation,

01:55:41.000 --> 01:55:44.000
and he was late for 20 minutes.

01:55:44.000 --> 01:55:47.000
And we got the following task.

01:55:47.000 --> 01:55:50.000
It also went down.

01:55:50.000 --> 01:55:53.000
We start to get nervous.

01:55:53.000 --> 01:55:57.000
We drive ourselves into a state of stress.

01:55:57.000 --> 01:56:00.000
This is never useful for the cause,

01:56:00.000 --> 01:56:03.000
especially for us.

01:56:03.000 --> 01:56:06.000
If we leave a gap between the cases,

01:56:06.000 --> 01:56:10.000
if we leave large time blocks unoccupied,

01:56:10.000 --> 01:56:14.000
it means that no matter how tough the tasks are,

01:56:14.000 --> 01:56:18.000
we will always have time to solve them.

01:56:19.000 --> 01:56:22.000
We will have time to solve them,

01:56:22.000 --> 01:56:26.000
as well as to solve some important tasks.

01:56:32.000 --> 01:56:35.000
Let's sum up the day's planning.

01:56:35.000 --> 01:56:38.000
Pay attention to the following slide.

01:56:38.000 --> 01:56:41.000
So, we don't dive into the working day.

01:56:41.000 --> 01:56:44.000
We don't rush to complete tasks

01:56:44.000 --> 01:56:47.000
that we have already planned.

01:56:47.000 --> 01:56:51.000
We clearly allocate 5-10 minutes for planning.

01:56:51.000 --> 01:56:55.000
We write down a list of our flexible tasks.

01:56:55.000 --> 01:56:59.000
We check again if there are any new tough meetings.

01:56:59.000 --> 01:57:02.000
How can we do this?

01:57:02.000 --> 01:57:06.000
Our diaries are not made to allocate a separate place

01:57:06.000 --> 01:57:09.000
for tough meetings.

01:57:09.000 --> 01:57:13.000
We have to make sure that we have a list of tasks

01:57:13.000 --> 01:57:17.000
that we can allocate a separate place for.

01:57:17.000 --> 01:57:20.000
It's very simple.

01:57:20.000 --> 01:57:24.000
We can divide a standard diary in half,

01:57:24.000 --> 01:57:27.000
if it's big enough.

01:57:27.000 --> 01:57:31.000
Or if the diary is not big enough,

01:57:31.000 --> 01:57:35.000
we write down tough meetings in it

01:57:35.000 --> 01:57:39.000
and allocate a place for some budgetary tasks.

01:57:40.000 --> 01:57:44.000
We can also write down a list of tasks

01:57:44.000 --> 01:57:48.000
on a piece of paper or a big diary page.

01:57:57.000 --> 01:58:00.000
I prefer the second option.

01:58:00.000 --> 01:58:04.000
I prefer to keep a list of flexible tasks

01:58:04.000 --> 01:58:07.000
in my diary.

01:58:07.000 --> 01:58:11.000
I prefer to write down the tasks that we have already completed.

01:58:11.000 --> 01:58:14.000
Some people like to write down the tasks

01:58:14.000 --> 01:58:17.000
on a separate piece of paper.

01:58:17.000 --> 01:58:20.000
They want to tear the paper

01:58:20.000 --> 01:58:23.000
and throw it away.

01:58:23.000 --> 01:58:26.000
If you feel comfortable with this,

01:58:26.000 --> 01:58:29.000
you can do it this way.

01:58:29.000 --> 01:58:32.000
So,

01:58:33.000 --> 01:58:36.000
the second point.

01:58:36.000 --> 01:58:39.000
We measure the toughness of the planning tool

01:58:39.000 --> 01:58:42.000
with the nature of the task.

01:58:42.000 --> 01:58:45.000
Is it a flexible or budgetary task?

01:58:45.000 --> 01:58:49.000
We try not to tie flexible tasks to the schedule.

01:58:49.000 --> 01:58:52.000
Why?

01:58:52.000 --> 01:58:55.000
For a flexible response to new circumstances.

01:58:55.000 --> 01:58:58.000
And finally, the third important conclusion.

01:58:59.000 --> 01:59:02.000
The more air in the plan,

01:59:02.000 --> 01:59:05.000
the more reserves,

01:59:05.000 --> 01:59:08.000
the higher the probability of implementing the plan,

01:59:08.000 --> 01:59:11.000
the higher the simplicity of changing the plan

01:59:11.000 --> 01:59:14.000
during the day.

01:59:14.000 --> 01:59:17.000
And finally,

01:59:17.000 --> 01:59:20.000
our conclusion on the whole block of planning.

01:59:20.000 --> 01:59:23.000
The next slide.

01:59:23.000 --> 01:59:26.000
Planning is not something tough.

01:59:26.000 --> 01:59:29.000
Planning is about how to complete a task

01:59:29.000 --> 01:59:32.000
in the best time for it.

01:59:32.000 --> 01:59:35.000
Next, we manage our tasks consciously.

01:59:35.000 --> 01:59:38.000
Everyone should know

01:59:38.000 --> 01:59:41.000
that we always use a convenient moment

01:59:41.000 --> 01:59:44.000
to solve our tasks.

01:59:44.000 --> 01:59:47.000
And finally,

01:59:47.000 --> 01:59:50.000
planning should be oriented to the result.

01:59:50.000 --> 01:59:53.000
And for this we use result-oriented formulations.

01:59:54.000 --> 01:59:57.000
And now we finish the discussion on the topic of planning

01:59:57.000 --> 02:00:00.000
and move on to a very important block,

02:00:00.000 --> 02:00:03.000
the block of self-motivation

02:00:03.000 --> 02:00:06.000
or self-struggle.

02:00:06.000 --> 02:00:09.000
So,

02:00:09.000 --> 02:00:12.000
how often do you rest during the working day?

02:00:12.000 --> 02:00:15.000
Not at all?

02:00:15.000 --> 02:00:18.000
Do you rest for 5 minutes?

02:00:18.000 --> 02:00:21.000
During lunch?

02:00:22.000 --> 02:00:25.000
I think I hear all these replicas.

02:00:25.000 --> 02:00:28.000
Maybe many others.

02:00:28.000 --> 02:00:31.000
In fact, there are a lot of possibilities

02:00:31.000 --> 02:00:34.000
and a lot of scenarios

02:00:34.000 --> 02:00:37.000
of a 5-minute effective rest

02:00:37.000 --> 02:00:40.000
during our working day.

02:00:40.000 --> 02:00:43.000
And you must rest,

02:00:43.000 --> 02:00:46.000
because typical mistakes of work load

02:00:46.000 --> 02:00:49.000
are reduced to the following.

02:00:49.000 --> 02:00:52.000
First,

02:00:52.000 --> 02:00:55.000
rest is spontaneous.

02:00:55.000 --> 02:00:58.000
It is not planned and organized consciously.

02:00:58.000 --> 02:01:01.000
Second,

02:01:01.000 --> 02:01:04.000
rest is not rhythmical.

02:01:04.000 --> 02:01:07.000
We do not have clear rules

02:01:07.000 --> 02:01:10.000
about the frequency and time of rest.

02:01:10.000 --> 02:01:13.000
And finally,

02:01:13.000 --> 02:01:16.000
we do not have well-thought-out scenarios of rest.

02:01:16.000 --> 02:01:19.000
Why do we have a problem every 45 minutes?

02:01:19.000 --> 02:01:22.000
Because children are not able to immerse themselves

02:01:22.000 --> 02:01:25.000
in a problem for more than 45 minutes.

02:01:25.000 --> 02:01:28.000
Why do we have a problem

02:01:28.000 --> 02:01:31.000
in educational institutions?

02:01:31.000 --> 02:01:34.000
Why do we have a problem

02:01:34.000 --> 02:01:37.000
in a couple of academic hours?

02:01:37.000 --> 02:01:40.000
Why?

02:01:40.000 --> 02:01:43.000
Because we are not able to do it.

02:01:43.000 --> 02:01:46.000
In fact, it is even worse.

02:01:46.000 --> 02:01:49.000
Every 20 minutes we need to change our activities.

02:01:49.000 --> 02:01:52.000
This is a perfect state.

02:01:52.000 --> 02:01:55.000
But in fact,

02:01:55.000 --> 02:01:58.000
the essential need

02:01:58.000 --> 02:02:01.000
is a 5-minute rest once an hour.

02:02:01.000 --> 02:02:04.000
It is not necessary

02:02:04.000 --> 02:02:07.000
that we should interrupt

02:02:07.000 --> 02:02:10.000
the execution of our budgetary tasks

02:02:10.000 --> 02:02:13.000
and stop resting.

02:02:13.000 --> 02:02:16.000
No, it is not like that.

02:02:16.000 --> 02:02:19.000
We are distracting ourselves.

02:02:19.000 --> 02:02:22.000
And this is wrong.

02:02:22.000 --> 02:02:25.000
Of course, when we are immersed,

02:02:25.000 --> 02:02:28.000
when we are focused on the development

02:02:28.000 --> 02:02:31.000
of a business plan,

02:02:31.000 --> 02:02:34.000
or we are engaged in some kind of report,

02:02:34.000 --> 02:02:37.000
or we are writing an article.

02:02:37.000 --> 02:02:40.000
Of course, we should not be distracted.

02:02:40.000 --> 02:02:43.000
But in routine,

02:02:43.000 --> 02:02:46.000
in a flow,

02:02:46.000 --> 02:02:49.000
it is desirable to pull yourself out

02:02:49.000 --> 02:02:52.000
of this routine state and switch.

02:02:52.000 --> 02:02:55.000
This is also our investment

02:02:55.000 --> 02:02:58.000
in our health,

02:02:58.000 --> 02:03:01.000
in our resourceful state during the day,

02:03:01.000 --> 02:03:04.000
in our adequate perception of problems

02:03:04.000 --> 02:03:07.000
and in a normal friendly attitude

02:03:07.000 --> 02:03:10.000
to all people around us.

02:03:10.000 --> 02:03:13.000
So, what are the principles of effective rest?

02:03:13.000 --> 02:03:16.000
Attention to the next slide.

02:03:16.000 --> 02:03:19.000
The first is that the rest should be rhythmic,

02:03:19.000 --> 02:03:22.000
5 minutes per hour.

02:03:22.000 --> 02:03:25.000
The second is that there should be maximum switching.

02:03:25.000 --> 02:03:28.000
And the third is the maximum change of the context.

02:03:28.000 --> 02:03:31.000
Vladimir Vladimirovich Mayakovsky said this best.

02:03:32.000 --> 02:03:35.000
Comrade, remember the rules of the simple.

02:03:35.000 --> 02:03:38.000
You work while sitting,

02:03:38.000 --> 02:03:41.000
rest while standing.

02:03:41.000 --> 02:03:44.000
And we really pay attention

02:03:44.000 --> 02:03:47.000
to the fact that the ideal rest

02:03:47.000 --> 02:03:50.000
is a rest that switches us

02:03:50.000 --> 02:03:53.000
from one activity to another as much as possible.

02:03:53.000 --> 02:03:56.000
If we were sitting at the computer,

02:03:56.000 --> 02:03:59.000
got up, stretched,

02:04:00.000 --> 02:04:03.000
did some microscopic gymnastics,

02:04:03.000 --> 02:04:06.000
very tiny,

02:04:06.000 --> 02:04:09.000
drank a cup of freshly brewed tea,

02:04:09.000 --> 02:04:12.000
pulled ourselves out of the workplace,

02:04:12.000 --> 02:04:15.000
walked, brewed this tea,

02:04:15.000 --> 02:04:18.000
came to the window,

02:04:18.000 --> 02:04:21.000
looked what was heard on the street,

02:04:21.000 --> 02:04:24.000
that is, pulled yourself out of the context.

02:04:24.000 --> 02:04:27.000
If, on the contrary,

02:04:27.000 --> 02:04:30.000
you were traveling all day,

02:04:30.000 --> 02:04:33.000
you were running all day,

02:04:33.000 --> 02:04:36.000
you were discussing something with someone all day,

02:04:36.000 --> 02:04:39.000
then, on the contrary, sit down,

02:04:39.000 --> 02:04:42.000
close your eyes,

02:04:42.000 --> 02:04:45.000
as our colleagues from Japan did on the slide,

02:04:45.000 --> 02:04:48.000
and take a little nap.

